[Vortrag] Fluorescence fluctuation methods in biophysical research

Optical methods exploiting fluorescence are particularly suitable for research of living matter on the microscopic scales, thanks to the possibility to selectively label the desired molecule with a fluorescent tag, and to detect its signal with high sensitivity. Fluorescence microscopy determines the spatial distribution of the labelled molecules, however with limited temporal resolution. Imaging can be supplemented by the analysis of fluctuating fluorescence signal originating from a small volume, yielding quantitative information about the photophysical properties of molecules, molecular mobilities, and intermolecular interactions on the scales from nanoseconds to seconds. The method analyzing fluorescence fluctuations, Fluorescence Correlation Spectroscopy, is used to study transport and association and dissociation reactions in solution, in model systems, such as phospholipid membranes, and even in vivo. The quantitative data obtained in this way are essential for theoretical modelling of biophysical processes. New developments and applications of fluorescence fluctuation methods, including spatio-temporal correlation and two-photon excitation, will be presented.<br>

[Vortrag] Analysis and Intervention in the Dynamics of Genetic Regulatory Networks

Analysis and intervention in the dynamics of genetic regulatory networks is at the heart of emerging efforts in the development of modern treatment of numerous ailments including cancer. The ultimate goal is to develop methods to intervene in the function of living organisms in order to drive cells away from a malignant state into a benign form. We formulate the optimal intervention problem in genetic regulatory networks as aminimal-perturbation of the network in order to force it to converge to a desired steady-state distribution of gene regulation. We cast optimal intervention in gene regulation as a convex optimization problem, thus providing a globally optimal solution which can be efficiently computed using standard techniques for convex optimization. We show that the optimal inverse perturbation control is robust to estimation errors in the original network. The proposed control is applied to the Human melanoma gene regulatory network.<br>
[Vortrag] Observing Romantic Encounters on the Nanoscale

I will present two methods for the observation of interactions between biomoleculeswith sensors featuring nano-scale functionalities. Artificial nanopores in solid state membranes are capable of detecting single molecules in a straightforward electrical measurement. When placing molecular receptor inside the pore, the device adopts chemical functionality and can be used to selectively discriminate biomolecules. As a paradigm for stochastic sensing, we analyse protein interactions on the single molecule level. The ”switchSENSE” principle is based on an electrically actuated bio-interface. Short DNA molecules are driven to oscillate (switch their conformation) on microelectrodes through the application of AC potentials. The induced molecular motion is monitored in real-time and not only reveals the mere presence of biomolecular targets on the sensor surface, but also permits the analysis of the target molecule size, shape, and charge in a single experiment.The implications for a novel type of protein biochip will be discussed.<br>
